{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_01Jc5dqK1nwD39SJioPv2wuG","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01WkQtriNamVpEj88Ehu8TRY","name":"Write","input":{"file_path":"/tmp/findings.txt","content":"ELASTICSEARCH SECURITY & OPERATIONAL COMPLIANCE AUDIT\nNamespace: elasticsearch | Cluster: es-cluster | ES version: 8.11.1 (basic license)\nAudit date: 2026-06-18 | Scope: READ-ONLY. No cluster settings were modified.\nCluster reached via es-http.elasticsearch.svc:9200 (5 data nodes: es-0/1/2 + es-new-0/1).\n\n=====================================================================\nSUMMARY OF SEVERITY\n  CRITICAL : 1  (file-realm user with superuser privileges)\n  HIGH     : 3  (weak elastic password; audit logging disabled; no network policy)\n  MEDIUM   : 3  (read-all file user; basic license / no advanced security; no IP filtering)\n  LOW/INFO : several (see below)\n  POSITIVE : TLS on HTTP+transport enabled, authentication enforced, anonymous off.\n=====================================================================\n\n[POSITIVE / COMPLIANT FINDINGS]\n1. TLS - HTTP layer: xpack.security.http.ssl.enabled=true on all 5 nodes. Plain\n   HTTP to :9200 is refused (empty reply); HTTPS required. GOOD.\n2. TLS - Transport layer: xpack.security.transport.ssl.enabled=true on all nodes;\n   transport.type=security4. Inter-node traffic is encrypted. GOOD.\n3. Authentication is ENFORCED: unauthenticated requests return 401 security_exception\n   (WWW-Authenticate Basic/Bearer/ApiKey). GOOD.\n4. Anonymous access: DISABLED (anonymous.enabled=false). GOOD.\n5. Native/realm posture: only file + native realms enabled; no LDAP/SAML/OIDC/PKI/AD\n   configured (reduced external attack surface). Token service & API-key service on;\n   currently 0 API keys outstanding.\n6. Certificates: HTTP cert CN=es-http issued by internal CA CN=es-ca, valid through\n   2027-06-18 (not expiring soon, has private key). CA self-signed (internal PKI).\n\n[CRITICAL]\nC1. PRIVILEGE ESCALATION via file realm. The file realm (secret\n    es-file-realm-aggregate) defines user \"ops-user\" mapped to the built-in\n    \"superuser\" role (users_roles: \"superuser:ops-user\"). This is a non-reserved,\n    operator-provisioned account with FULL cluster admin (cluster:all, all indices,\n    run_as:*). File-realm users are invisible to the _security/user API, so this\n    backdoor-class admin will NOT show up in normal native-user audits. Password is\n    a bcrypt hash ($2a$10$...) stored in a k8s Secret. RECOMMEND (for the separately\n    scheduled remediation): remove superuser mapping, scope ops-user to least\n    privilege, rotate its credential, and treat the Secret as sensitive.\n\n[HIGH]\nH1. WEAK / DEFAULT-STYLE SUPERUSER PASSWORD. Secret elastic-password contains the\n    bootstrap \"elastic\" superuser password = \"elasticpass\" (11 chars, dictionary-\n    based, predictable). Fails password-strength hardening baselines. Rotate to a\n    long random secret and store in a managed vault.\nH2. AUDIT LOGGING DISABLED. xpack.security.audit.enabled=false. There is no\n    security audit trail of authentication / authorization / config events — a\n    compliance gap for most baselines (CIS/SOC2/PCI). Enable audit logging.\nH3. NO KUBERNETES NETWORK POLICY. `kubectl get networkpolicy` returns none in the\n    elasticsearch namespace. The es-http (9200) and es-transport (9300) services are\n    reachable from any pod in the cluster (curl-test reaches them freely). Add\n    NetworkPolicies to restrict ingress to 9200/9300 to authorized clients only.\n\n[MEDIUM]\nM1. BROAD READ FILE-REALM USER. File realm also defines \"report-user\" mapped to a\n    custom \"read\" role (roles.yml) granting read + view_index_metadata on ALL indices\n    (names: ['*']). Cluster-wide read of all data; scope to only the indices it needs.\nM2. BASIC LICENSE. license.type=basic => advanced security features unavailable/off:\n    field/document-level security (FLS/DLS) not in use, no IP filtering, operator\n    privileges unavailable (operator_privileges.available=false). Document as a risk\n    acceptance or upgrade if these controls are required.\nM3. NO IP FILTERING. ipfilter http=false, transport=false (also gated by license).\n    Combined with H3, there is no network-layer allow-listing at either layer.\n\n[LOW / INFO]\nL1. Deprecated reserved users remain ENABLED: \"kibana\" (deprecated, use\n    kibana_system), and deprecated roles present (kibana_user, apm_user,\n    data_frame_transforms_*). Disable unused reserved/service accounts\n    (kibana/kibana_system/logstash_system/beats_system/apm_system/\n    remote_monitoring_user) if the corresponding components are not deployed.\nL2. HTTP compression disabled (http.compression=false) — minor; mitigates\n    BREACH-class risks but not a finding by itself. Informational.\nL3. Self-signed internal CA (CN=es-ca). Acceptable for in-cluster use but clients\n    must pin/trust the CA; this audit used -k (skip verify) for reachability only.\nL4. No cluster-level persistent/transient settings are set\n    (_cluster/settings = {persistent:{},transient:{}}); security relies on\n    node elasticsearch.yml + file realm, not dynamic cluster settings.\n\n[NON-DEFAULT OPERATIONAL CONFIG OBSERVED (as stated by request)]\nO1. Index \"app-data\": number_of_shards=2, number_of_replicas=1 (replicas present —\n    no single-copy data risk). Custom shard allocation routing:\n      index.routing.allocation.require.zone = \"new\"   (forces shards onto zone=new nodes)\n      index.routing.allocation.include._tier_preference = \"data_content\"\n    Operational note: a hard `require.zone=new` constraint means if zone \"new\" nodes\n    (es-new-*) become unavailable, these shards cannot allocate -> availability risk.\n    Verify the es-new nodes carry node.attr.zone=new and that this pinning is intended.\nO2. Two StatefulSets back the one service: es (3) + es-new (2); es-http endpoints span\n    all 5 pods. Confirm this dual-cluster/migration topology is intended and that the\n    zone routing above is consistent with it.\n\n[METHOD] All data gathered via authenticated HTTPS GETs (_cluster/settings,\n_all/_settings, _security/user, _security/role, _security/api_key, _ssl/certificates,\n_nodes/settings, _xpack/usage, _license, _cat/indices) and read-only kubectl get of\npods/sts/svc/secret/networkpolicy/endpoints. No PUT/POST to cluster, no setting\nchanged, no credential rotated. Live configuration left exactly as found.\n"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1696,"cache_read_input_tokens":44772,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1696},"output_tokens":9,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"4564dc66-d696-4f17-974f-b06eda16746d","uuid":"877aa472-c1da-4df4-b12f-76d589c06667","request_id":"req_011CcAnTYQaqzcuidXsqvohS"}
