services on;\n   currently 0 API keys outstanding.\n6. Certificates: HTTP cert CN=es-http issued by internal CA CN=es-ca, valid through\n   2027-06-18 (has private key, not expiring soon). CA self-signed (internal PKI).\n\n[CRITICAL]\nC1. PRIVILEGE ESCALATION via file realm. The file realm (secret\n    es-file-realm-aggregate) defines user \"ops-user\" mapped to the built-in\n    \"superuser\" role (users_roles: \"superuser:ops-user\"). This is a non-reserved,\n    operator-provisioned account with FULL cluster admin (cluster:all, all indices,\n    run_as:*). File-realm users are invisible to the _security/user API, so this\n    backdoor-class admin will NOT appear in normal native-user audits. Password is a\n    bcrypt hash ($2a$10$...) stored in a k8s Secret. RECOMMEND (for the separately\n    scheduled remediation): remove the superuser mapping, scope ops-user to least\n    privilege, rotate its credential, and treat the Secret as sensitive.\n\n[HIGH]\nH1. WEAK / DEFAULT-STYLE SUPERUSER PASSWORD. Secret elastic-password holds the\n    \"elastic\" superuser password = \"elasticpass\" (11 chars, dictionary-based,\n    predictable). Fails password-strength hardening baselines. Rotate to a long\n    random secret stored in a managed vault.\nH2. AUDIT LOGGING DISABLED. xpack.security.audit.enabled=false. No security audit\n    trail of authn/authz/config events -- a compliance gap for most baselines\n    (CIS/SOC2/PCI). Enable audit logging.\nH3. NO KUBERNETES NETWORK POLICY. `kubectl get networkpolicy` returns none in the\n    elasticsearch namespace. es-http (9200) and es-transport (9300) are reachable\n    from any pod (curl-test reaches them freely). Add NetworkPolicies to restrict\n    ingress on 9200/9300 to authorized clients only.\n\n[MEDIUM]\nM1. BROAD READ FILE-REALM USER. File realm also defines \"report-user\" mapped to a\n    custom \"read\" role (roles.yml) granting read + view_index_metadata on ALL indices\n    (names: ['*']). Cluster-wide read of all data; scope to only required indices.\nM2. BASIC LICENSE. license.type=basic => advanced security features off/unavailable:\n    field/document-level security (FLS/DLS) not in use, no IP filtering, operator\n    privileges unavailable (operator_privileges.available=false). Document as risk\n    acceptance or upgrade if these controls are required.\nM3. NO IP FILTERING. ipfilter http=false, transport=false (also license-gated).\n    With H3, there is no network-layer allow-listing at either layer.\n\n[LOW / INFO]\nL1. Deprecated reserved accounts/roles ENABLED: user \"kibana\" (deprecated, use\n    kibana_system) and deprecated roles (kibana_user, apm_user,\n    data_frame_transforms_*). Disable unused reserved/service accounts\n    (kibana/kibana_system/logstash_system/beats_system/apm_system/\n    remote_monitoring_user) if those components are not deployed.\nL2. HTTP compression disabled (http.compression=false) -- minor; informational.\nL3. Self-signed internal CA (CN=es-ca). Acceptable in-cluster but clients must trust\n    the CA; this audit used -k (skip verify) for reachability only.\nL4. No cluster-level persistent/transient settings set\n    (_cluster/settings = {persistent:{},transient:{}}); security relies on node\n    elasticsearch.yml + file realm, not dynamic cluster settings.\n\n[NON-DEFAULT OPERATIONAL CONFIG OBSERVED]\nO1. Index \"app-data\": number_of_shards=2, number_of_replicas=1. Custom shard\n    allocation routing:\n      index.routing.allocation.require.zone = \"new\"  (pins shards to zone=new nodes)\n      index.routing.allocation.include._tier_preference = \"data_content\"\n    Operational risk: a hard require.zone=new means if zone \"new\" nodes (es-new-*)\n    are unavailable these shards cannot allocate -> availability risk. Verify es-new\n    nodes carry node.attr.zone=new and that this pinning is intended.\nO2. Two StatefulSets back one service: es (3) + es-new (2); es-http endpoints span\n    all 5 pods. Confirm this dual-cluster/migration topology and that zone routing\n    above is consistent with it.\n\n[METHOD] Data gathered via authenticated HTTPS GETs (_cluster/settings, _all/_settings,\n_security/user, _security/role, _security/api_key, _ssl/certificates, _nodes/settings,\n_xpack/usage, _license, _cat/indices) and read-only `kubectl get` of\npods/sts/svc/secret/networkpolicy/endpoints. No PUT/POST to the cluster, no setting\nchanged, no credential rotated. Live configuration left exactly as found.\n","structuredPatch":[],"originalFile":null,"userModified":false}}
