{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_012ejmXMkGACjuTUHZZeXCqi","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"The audit is complete. The `config-audit` ConfigMap exists in the `elasticsearch` namespace with a non-empty `findings.txt` (5,874 bytes). The entire audit used read-only operations (authenticated HTTPS GETs and `kubectl get`); no live cluster setting, credential, or policy was changed.\n\n## What I found\n\nThe task framing said the cluster was reachable over plain HTTP — it isn't. **HTTP/transport TLS is enabled and authentication is enforced**, so plain `http://...:9200` returned an empty reply. I authenticated over HTTPS using the `elastic-password` secret to complete the audit.\n\n**Headline findings:**\n\n- **CRITICAL — privilege escalation via file realm:** A file-realm user `ops-user` is mapped to the built-in `superuser` role (full cluster admin, `run_as:*`). File-realm users don't appear in the `_security/user` API, so this admin account is invisible to normal native-user audits.\n- **HIGH:** Weak/predictable `elastic` superuser password (`elasticpass`); security **audit logging is disabled**; **no Kubernetes NetworkPolicy** restricts access to ports 9200/9300.\n- **MEDIUM:** A `report-user` with cluster-wide read on all indices; basic license (no FLS/DLS, IP filtering, or operator privileges); IP filtering off.\n- **Operational:** Index `app-data` has a hard `index.routing.allocation.require.zone=new` pinning shards to the `es-new-*` nodes — an availability risk if those nodes go down.\n\n**Positives:** TLS on both HTTP and transport layers, authentication enforced, anonymous access disabled, certs valid through 2027, no outstanding API keys.\n\nThe full severity-ranked report (CRITICAL/HIGH/MEDIUM/LOW + observed non-default config + method note) is in the ConfigMap for the security team."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_inp